Python for data Science Project¶

Author Jose Andres Castañeda Forno

Project Description¶

This project will explain the development of a Machine learning model step by step. The dataset we will be working with is an MLB pitching statistics from the official site MLB Savant, https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/statcast_search .

Now days with the technology available, the sports industry has evolved and most, if not all, of plays are being tracked by sensors and cameras, recopilating that data is gold for the teams, as it allows them to analyse players performance, field conditions, etc, and take smarter desitions based on data. One particular field of interes for MLB teams is pitching performance, is a very important topic not only for the teams, but also for the fans. Most brodcast chanels show pitching stats on live games that allows users to better understand the game, one specific stat is the pitch type (shown most of the times on the top corner) It indicates and classifies the pitch thrown by the pithcer (Fastball, Cutter, Slider, etc) each pith has a peculiar moevement that allows them to "classifiy/name" the pitch as shown in the next video.

Pitch moevment: https://www.youtube.com/shorts/tPX76PGNYZU
pitch type: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s0woX8UVvY4&t=32s

Project objective¶

This project aims to develop a classification model, the main objective is to assign the correct name to each pitch based on the metrics collected by the sensors on the field. We know that every team measures features of the pitch like the speed, spin rate, break angle, etc. All of this information is available on the MLB Savant website, using that information, the model will have to correctlly classify and "name" the pitch.

Dataset Description¶

As we will se later MLB Savant keeps track of all the events that occure on the field, but we are only interested on the pitching events, in other words, how the ball is traveling from the pitchers hand to home plate. This dataset contains multiple features, will dig dipper later, for every pitch thrown in every official game, so as you can imagine, we have a couple of thowsands rows of data to play with. This features are the once use by the MLB in their sistems to classify the pitches, so we have what we need to work here.

Expert knowledge filter dataset¶

As we can observe, the dataset is populated with a lot of features that are useful for the MLB teams to keep track of the situation of the game, but most of them are not useful for our model.

In order to reduce the number of features we first apply a "Expert knowledge filter" to this dataset, that is, someone with experience on the game and pitching (me) has a really good idea of what features are possible to have an impact on the prediction of the pitch. In this step the so called "expert" must to be careful of not removing posible features with strong prediction/classification power in our model. Features like, the date of the game, the name of the players, the score of the game, etc. Are mot really important to classify the pitch, thats why, we will stick with the most promising features listed bellow:

Labels:

  • pitch_name and pitch_type : This is our objective, the pitch type threw by the pitcher (are the same, so we only keep pitch_name).

Promising features:

  • release_speed : Initial velocity of the pitch.
  • release_pos_x / release_pos_z : Release point of the pitch (2D).
  • p_trows : Indicates if the pitcher is lefty or righty (important because of the spin direction of the ball).
  • pfx_x / pfx_x : Break (movement) of the ball during the trajectory (2D).
  • spin_axis : Axis of rotation of the ball.
  • release_spin_rate : Spin rate at the moment of release

Features exploration¶

Now with only the promising features we are going to start exploring them and understand the data we are working with.

Pitches classification objective¶

Observing at the pitches distribution we have a better idea about what pitches our model will be able to classify better. As we can see, the 4-seam fastball is the prefer pitch type, but after the cutter we see that the other pitches are no so commonly thrown.

Here we have an important piece of information, the pitches with less information or concurrencies are going to be harder to classify correctly because the model is not going to be able to "learn" the characteristics of them, one posible option to this problem is to exclude those type of pitches from the prediction list and work only with the most concurrent once:

List of pitches to predict:

  • 4-Seam Fastball
  • Slider
  • Sinker
  • Changeup
  • Curveball
  • Cutter

This, form a "Bussines/Experts" point of view, is a good starting point, most of the pitchers have this types of pitches in their roster and is very uncommon to have a pithcer throwing a knuckleball (1 or 2 in all the leage with more than 150 pitchers).

Pitch types description: https://www.mlb.com/glossary/pitch-types

Pitch Break¶

This graph shows us the difference between the different pitch types and the pitchers arm side (left or right). The red line in the middle of the figure is representing the center of home plate and it also works to represent the "axis of symmetry" between lefties and righties, as we can observe the effect of the ball from each arside is almos perfectly symetric to this line, pitches from each arm side are split by this line.

At the same time, we observe the behaivor of the different pitch types. The curveball (Yellow) is a breaking pitch with strong movement towards the floor and the 4-seam Fastball (orange) is a pitch without movement. We clearly see the position of the curveball on the lower part and the fastballs not breaking down at all. At the same time we observa again the symetry of each arm side.

Pitch initial velocity¶

Another important feature to evaluate a pitch is the speed of release, as we can observe differrent pitch types have differente velocities. In order for the ball to move "break", the pitch must be released with different speed and spin velocities.

In both figures we observe that the fastball, ball without movement but fast, has the highes release speed. The curveball not so fast but breaking a lot, has a lower release sepped but the highest spin rate. This is one part of how pitchers manage to throw different pitches and dominate batters.

Pitch initial spin rate¶

Spin rate is an important metric in baseball analytics because it can influence a pitcher's ability to control the ball, deceive hitters, and generate movement on different pitches. Pitchers with high spin rates, particularly on breaking balls like curveballs and sliders, often create more movement and can be more challenging for batters to track.

Spin Axis - For each side (L and R)¶

The axis of rotation of the ball is something really important to take into account for this mode, as we can observe in the following image the axis of rotation is almost symetryc between lefties and righties. This figure ilustrates the angel of the axis of rotation of the ball when spinning after the picher releases the ball. A curveball for example, will spin with the same magnitude but in different "sides" for lefties and righties, due to the nature of the arm pitch. We can make the analogy to soccer, in a free kick, left kicker can make the ball move towards one direction and a rigth kicker will make the ball move towards the oposite direction, each one of them is making the ball have a symetric axis of rotation.

Feature engineering¶

Feature - Lefty feature¶

We will create a feature that indicates if the pitcher is lefty or not, this is important because of the rotation of the ball, the ball from a lefty rotates in the oposite direction than from a righty as we can observe in the "Spin Axis - For each side (L and R)" Figure. So the curveball from a lefty fill have the same "magnitud" but different axis of rotation.

To work with this, we will encode label encoding the p_throws feature (Lefty or Righty to a 1 or 0). As models work better with numbers than with text.

In [37]:
df_pitches["lefty"] = 0
df_pitches.loc[df_pitches["p_throws"] == 'L', 'lefty'] = 1

Feature - Power of rotation¶

To use the same magnitud for both lefties and righties the we create a new feature called power_rotation multiplying the release_spin_rate and the pin_axis , this will give us a mix of the "power and direction" of the spin of the ball and we multiply by -1 (only for lefties) in order to have the same "direction" from both pitchers sides.

In [39]:
df_pitches["power_rotation"] = np.where(df_pitches["lefty"],
        (df_pitches["spin_axis"] -180) * df_pitches["release_spin_rate"] * -1,
        (df_pitches["spin_axis"] -180) * df_pitches["release_spin_rate"]                         
)

Has we can observe in the next figure, all the pitches now have the same "power_rotation", and for both lefties and righties the magnitudes and direction match. Another observation is that only the slider and the curveball have a negative magnitud and it makes sens, those are the only two pitches with a rotation towards home plate, the other ones rotate in the opposite direction.

Feature - Aggressiveness¶

Another feature that we will evaluate is the "aggressiveness", two pitches can have the same "power of rotation" but not the same speed, so for this feature we are taking into account the "release_speed" of the ball.

In [41]:
df_pitches["aggressiveness"] = df_pitches["power_rotation"] / df_pitches["release_speed"]

Encode the labels into numerical values¶

We will enconde the labels and assign a numeric value to each categoriacal value in the list. This is due to the fact that model works better with numerical values than with text. We also store the "mapping" between the category and the actual value so later we can "remap" the output to a more human friendly answer.

In [43]:

Prepare the sets (Training set, Validation set, Test set)¶

The initial aproach for this problem will be

Logistic Regression¶

Training the model¶

We start by trining the logistic regression model with the training data, so it can "learn" about the data. This model fits the probabilistic function that indicates the probability of some output category being true, in this case the outputs are the pitch types, so the model will give us a table with the probability of each pitch being the correct one.

Measure the model¶

Accuracy¶

The accuracy of a classification model tell us how many time the model classified correctly the entries compared to the total number of entries, in other words, out of 100 Cutters how many where classified as cutters.

Description: https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/crash-course/classification/accuracy

Scikit-learn function: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.accuracy_score.html

In [48]:
# produce accuracy and log loss metrics to evaluate model performance 
acc_lg = accuracy_score(validation_res['pitch_type'], validation_res.loc[:, 'pitch_type_pred'])
acc_lg
Out[48]:
0.8110807012352985

Loss¶

With the loss function we can have an indicator of the error between the prediction output and the correct target value. This means that the lower ther loss the closer the model is "missing" in comparison to the target value.

Here we observe a loss of 0.51, so when we fail we are failing considerably high. The prediction that the model gave is not close to the target value.

Scikit-learn function: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.log_loss.html

In [49]:

Conclusion¶

The logistic regression model has a acuracy of 81% wich is very good and a 0.51 loss, this model is a great first iteration to the problem and has set the line to the next model, so lets see how Random Forest performs.

Data Pre-processing¶

In [65]:
# Reduction of Features
features = ["release_speed", "pfx_x", "pfx_z", "release_spin_rate", "spin_axis", "pitch_name", "p_throws"] 
df_live = df_live[features]


# Data cleaning
df_live = df_live.dropna(subset=["pitch_name", "release_speed", "pfx_x", "pfx_z", "spin_axis", "release_spin_rate"])
df_live = df_live.reset_index(drop=True)


# Feature engineering 
# Is lefty
df_live["lefty"] = 0
df_live.loc[df_live["p_throws"] == 'L', 'lefty'] = 1


#  Power rotation
df_live["power_rotation"] = np.where(df_live["lefty"],
        (df_live["spin_axis"] -180) * df_live["release_spin_rate"] * -1,
        (df_live["spin_axis"] -180) * df_live["release_spin_rate"]                         
)

# Aggresivness
df_live["aggressiveness"] = df_live["power_rotation"] / df_live["release_speed"]


# Pitch encoding 
df_live = df_live[df_live["pitch_name"].isin(["4-Seam Fastball", "Slider", "Sinker", "Changeup", "Curveball", "Cutter"])]
categories = df_live["pitch_name"].astype('category')
df_live["pitch_code"] = categories.cat.codes
pitch_type_cat = categories.cat.categories



# Features and labels 
live_features  = ["release_speed", "pfx_x", "pfx_z", "release_spin_rate", "power_rotation", "aggressiveness"] 
live_label = "pitch_code"

Conclusion¶

After working on this project we can conclude:

  • Random fores model performs better than the logistic regression model as expected, Random Forest is a more complex model.
  • This model is highly accurate for predicting pitches with unseen data (Close to 90%).
  • The most important features are the once reprecenting the speed, rotation and break of the ball.

Recomendations¶

For the next iterations of this model is recomended to dig further in developing a efficient model to distinguish "really similar pitches" as we saw on the Evaluate hardes pitches to classify section is har for the model to classify correctlly similar movement pitches like the slider, the cutter and the curveball, in a real game the breake difference between these pitches can be a couple on centimeters and it depends on each pitchers arms side, release point, pitching style, etc. Its recomended to work on the feature engineering step to campure all that information and make the model more accurate.

Its also recommended to explore another models of classification to validate if one of them is more efficient (there is always room for improvement).

Self-critical assessment¶

During this project the most complex part was the feature analysis and engineering steps, here is where the real value of the project is. Selecting/creating the features and defining wich onces can give the model the complete "context" and information about the problem to accuratly classify the pitches. At the same time here is where the project could be improved, even thoug we have a good accuracy 90%, in the feature engineering step we can improve the "missing" information for the model to correcly classify that 10% left.

I think that this project needs spatial imagination and understanding, because the problem and all of the features are taken and representing a 3D fenomena, so having that spatial ability can really help to connect all the dots (feature) together, also having a couple of oranges as baseballs can help with the visualization.
